      <p>
        In general, nouns do not inherently have a difference in singular and plural forms.
        When refering to peole the suffix <a href='/word_detail.php?id=4760'>们</a> can be used to indcate more 
        than one person. For example,
        <a href='/word_detail.php?id=1724' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'tóngzhì', 'comrade')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">同志</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=4760' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '們 men', 'plural')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">们</a> (comrades),  
        <a href='/word_detail.php?id=2545' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'xiānsheng', 'Mr. / sir / mister / teacher / title of respect')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">先生</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=4760' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '們 men', 'plural')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">们</a> (gentlemen), and so on.
        “<a href='/word_detail.php?id=4760' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'men', 'plural')" onmouseout='hideToolTip()'>们</a>” should be pronounced with the neutral tone.
      </p>
