      <p>
        In general, a monosyllabic adjective can directly modify another word. For example, 
        <a href='/word_detail.php?id=491' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'bái', 'white')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">白</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=2472' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '紙 zhǐ', 'paper')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">纸</a>  (white paper).
        However, if you wish to emphasize the modified nature then you may use the particle 
        <a href='/word_detail.php?id=273' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'de', 'possessive particle')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">的</a>. For example, <a href='/word_detail.php?id=654' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'hěn', 'very')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">很</a><a href='/word_detail.php?id=3536' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'lěng', 'cold')" onmouseout="hideToolTip()">冷</a><span class='hl'>的</span><a href='/word_detail.php?id=3133' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, '天氣 tiānqì', 'weather')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">天气</a>  (very cold weather). 
        When a dissyllabic adjective modifies a monosyllabic noun then the particle 
        “<a href='/word_detail.php?id=273' onmouseover="showToolTip(this, 'de', 'possessive particle')" 
        onmouseout="hideToolTip()">的</a>” must be used. For example, 
